Statement of Actuarial Opinion Chubb Insurance Company of Puerto Rico
March 24, 2023
IDENTIFICATION
I, Alejandro Ortega, FCAS, MAAA, CFA am a consultant at Ortega Statistical Services. I was appointed by the Board of Directors of Chubb Insurance Company of Puerto Rico (the “Company”) on September 29, 2021 to provide this Actuarial Opinion. I meet the definition of a Qualified Actuary per the NAIC Annual Statement Instructions – Property and Casualty, Actuarial Opinion. I have provided my qualification Documentation to the Board of Directors through the Company’s management.
This opinion is written to comply with Rule 96 of the Office of the Commissioner of Insurance of Puerto Rico.
SCOPE
I have examined the actuarial assumptions and methods used in determining the reserves listed in Exhibit A, as shown in the Annual Statement of Chubb Insurance Company of Puerto Rico as prepared for filing with regulatory officials as, of December 31, 2022, and reviewed information provided to me through March 23, 2023.
The reserves listed in Exhibit A, where applicable, including provisions for Disclosure items (disclosures 8 through 13.2) in Exhibit B.
The loss reserves are on an undiscounted basis and include a provision for losses and loss adjustment expenses, net of reinsurance.
In forming my opinion on the loss and loss adjustment expenses reserves, I relied upon data prepared by staff under the direction of Jose Jimenez, Chief Financial Officer of the Company. I evaluated that data for reasonableness and consistency. I also reconciled the data to Schedule P, Parts 1-4. The data reconciled well, with one notable exception: property claims occurring in 2017, driven by Hurricane Maria; which as of this point the Net Reserves are $0, and thus the impact is negligible.
My review was limited to the items in Exhibit A, and I did not include an analysis of any income statement items or other balance sheet items. My opinion on the reserves is based upon the assumptions that all reserves are backed by valid assets, which have suitable scheduled maturities and/or adequate liquidity to meet cash flow requirements.

OPINION
In my opinion, the amounts carried in Exhibit A on account of the items identified:
Meet the requirements of the insurance laws of Puerto Rico,
Are consistent with reserves computed in accordance with accepted actuarial standards and principles,
. Make a reasonable provision for all unpaid loss and loss adjustment expense obligations of the Company under the terms of its contracts and agreements.
In aggregate, the Company’s stated reserves are within a reasonable range of my estimates of unpaid loss and loss adjustment expense amounts; hence, the stated reserve amounts make a reasonable provision for the liabilities associated with the specified reserves.
RELEVANT COMMENTS
Company Specific Risk Factors
Actuarial estimates of property and casualty loss and loss adjustment expenses reserves are inherently uncertain because they are dependent on future contingent events. Also, these reserve estimates are generally derived from analyses of historical data. Future events or conditions may differ from the past. The actual amount necessary to settle the unpaid claims may therefore be significantly different from the reserve amounts listed in Exhibit A.
The following are factors and conditions underlying the risks and uncertainties that I consider relevant to the Company’s estimates of unpaid losses and loss adjustment expenses as of December 31, 2022.
The company has substantial exposure to both Primary and Excess Liability and Financial Lines Products. These lines have loss development that can take several years, and be several million dollars.
The long reporting delay and the large amounts make these books highly uncertain. The company has the risk that several claims could develop late. Mitigating this risk is reinsurance that adequately reduces this risk.
RMAD
To determine the materiality standard I reviewed the following figures: 10% of Reserves, 20% of Surplus, and the surplus change required for the next RBC action level (200%).

In my analysis I considered the potential for adverse development in the Liability and Financial Lines products, and the implications of uncertainty in estimates of unpaid losses and loss adjustment expenses in determining a range of reasonable unpaid claim estimates. I have also observed that the

difference between the high end of my range of reasonable unpaid claim estimate and the Company’s carried reserves for losses and loss adjustment expense is less than my materiality standard. I further considered whether there are significant risks and uncertainties that could result in material adverse deviation. In light of the materiality considerations within this analysis, and after considering the potential risks and uncertainties that could bear on the Company’s reserve development, I concluded that those risks and uncertainties would not reasonably be expected to result in material adverse deviation in the Company's carried reserves for unpaid losses and loss adjustment expenses.
Salvage and Subrogation
Carried reserves are net of anticipated salvage and subrogation.
Discounting
The Company does not discount its reserves listed in Exhibit A for the time value of money.
Pools and Associations
The company does not participate in any voluntary or involuntary pools or associations.
Inflation
The loss data in the analysis is from the last 20 years, with the bulk of the data from the last 10 calendar years. In the 10 years, prior to 2021, the inflation in Puerto Rico has averaged 0.8% per year. In 2021 it was 4.2% and in 2022 was 6.0%, and has begun to level off.
Thus, there is the expectation that inflation will have an upward impact on the unpaid losses. This was implemented in the analysis by selecting expected loss ratios that are somewhat higher than the historical loss ratios. It is my expectation that this adjustment adequately compensates for the additional costs due to inflation.
Asbestos and Environmental
I have reviewed the Company’s exposure to environmental, pollution, and asbestos related claims and other claims from mass torts. The Company, through its participation in intercompany reinsurance agreements reinsured 100% of its liabilities on general liability policies issued prior to January 1, 1987. Thus, these types of claims are not expected to have a material effect on the company’s liability.
Reinsurance Collectability
A majority of the recoverables are to affiliated reinsurers, with authorized reinsurers making up most of the rest. Unauthorized reinsurers make up 1% of the reinsurance recoverable. I have reviewed the timeliness of payments on Schedule F, for the most part reinsurance recoverable has been paid on a timely basis. There are some amounts that are over 90 days overdue; a provision for reinsurance is held for these reinsurance recoverables (Schedule F penalty). Nearly all of the amount 90 days overdue is held by reinsurers with a Fitch rating of at least A+. The risk of uncollectable reinsurance is immaterial.
My opinion on the loss and loss adjustment expense reserves net of ceded reinsurance assumes that all ceded reinsurance is valid and collectable.
Retroactive Reinsurance and Financial Reinsurance
Based on discussions with Company management, and its description of the Company’s ceded reinsurance, I am not aware of any reinsurance contract that either has been or should have been accounted for as retroactive reinsurance or financial reinsurance.

##Page 4
SUPPLEMENT FOR THE YEAR 2022 OF THE Chubb Insurance Company of Puerto Rico
IRIS Ratios
I have examined the NAIC IRIS tests for One-Year Reserve Development to Surplus (Test 11), Two-Year Reserve Development to Surplus (Test 12), and Estimated Current Reserve Deficiency to Surplus (Test 13) no exceptional values were observed.
Changes in Methods and Assumptions
No material changes were made to the actuarial assumptions or methods from last year.
Covid-19 Considerations
The impacts of Covid-19 on the client were mostly on the premium. Many businesses had lower revenue and need for insurance, thus reducing the Company's written premium. New products were introduced that led to additional premium. For lines where Covid-19 may have had an impact on the lag to report or pay claims, these lines were reviewed on a more granular basis (quarterly), and adjustments were made as necessary. The impact of Covid-19 on the liabilities of the company were not material.
